    <div class="col-txt">
      <span class="eyebrow">03. What a Small World Holds</span>
      <h3>A child has a story <span class="it">long before</span> she has the words.</h3>

      <div class="body">
        <p><span class="dropcap">B</span>efore a child writes a sentence, she stages one. She walks a felt fox into the mossy cave, flies a butterfly across the lily pond, lifts the Gruffalo into the wood and out again. Small World is the toolkit for that staging: hand-felted habitat mats that hold a scene, finger puppets sized for small hands, and circle-time story sets that turn a familiar rhyme into something a body can do. No screens. No instructions. Just landscape, character, and the long, generous space between them.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="pillars">
        <div class="p"><span class="label">Narrative Play</span><p>The story before the word.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">Habitat Studies</span><p>Reef, meadow, forest, pond, one mat at a time.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">Oral Language</span><p>Songs, rhymes, retelling, vocabulary.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">Literacy &middot; Pre-K to Grade 2</span><p>Library story corners, Reggio piazzas.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

